JOHANNESBURG, July 4 (ANA) - A woman from Tunisia's moderate Islamic party has been elected as mayor of the capital city, Tunis, the first time a woman holds the post, AP reported. The North African country leads the Arab world in regard to womenâ€™s rights after gaining independence from France in 1956. Souad Abderrahim, a 54-year-old pharmacist of the Ennahdha party, won the post in the second round of voting by the municipal council after defeating her top rival, Kamel Idir, of the party Nida Tounes, founded by the Tunisian president. -	African News Agency (ANA)